This paper deals with mechanism design, which is a subfield of game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves approximation algorithms and optimization, which are common topics in computer science theory (cs.DS). The use of Bayesian methods and the focus on revenue extraction suggest a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also falls under the category of computational economics (cs.EC) due to its focus on designing mechanisms for economic settings. Finally, the use of mathematical analysis and probability theory suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.LG).
